    "summary": "On December 21, 1988, Pan Am Flight 103 exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing all 259 people aboard and 11 residents of Lockerbie struck by wreckage, for a total of 270 dead. The explosion was caused by a Semtex bomb hidden in a cassette player in the aircraft's luggage hold. The attack was the deadliest terrorist incident in British history and, at the time, the deadliest attack against American civilians since the Second World War.\n\nA painstaking international investigation eventually pointed to Libyan intelligence agents acting under orders from Muammar Gaddafi's government, believed to be retaliation for the 1986 US bombing of Libya. Two Libyan suspects were indicted in 1991, and years of diplomatic standoff followed before Libya surrendered them for trial in 1999 under a deal negotiated by the UN and brokered partly by South Africa's Nelson Mandela. The trial was conducted under Scottish law in the Netherlands; one defendant, Abdelbaset al-Megrahi, was convicted in 2001 while the other was acquitted. Al-Megrahi was released on compassionate grounds in 2009, dying of cancer in 2012 while maintaining his innocence, a decision that generated significant controversy.",
